drug.name: Obinutuzumab
drug.description: Obinutuzumab is a humanized monoclonal antibody used as a combination treatment with chlorambucil to treat patients with untreated chronic lymphocytic leukemia. It was approved by the FDA in November 2013 and is marketed under the brand name Gazyva. There is a black box warning of fatal Hepatitis B Virus (HBV) reactivation and fatal Progressive Multifocal Leukoencephalopathy (PML).
drug.synthesis-reference: Robak T: GA-101, a third-generation, humanized and glyco-engineered anti-CD20 mAb for the treatment of B-cell lymphoid malignancies. Curr Opin Investig Drugs. 2009 Jun;10(6):588-96.
drug.indication: Obinutuzumab is used as a combination treatment with chlorambucil to treat patients with untreated chronic lymphocytic leukemia.
drug.pharmacodynamics: Obinutuzumab is more potent than rituximab in depleting B-cells, antitumor activity, and tumor regression.
drug.mechanism-of-action: In contrast to rituximab, which is a classic type I CD20 antibody, obinutuzumab binds to type II CD20 antibodies. This allows obinutuzumab to have a much higher induction of antibody-dependant cytotoxicity and a higher direct cytotoxic effect than the classic CD20 antibodies.
drug.toxicity: The most serious toxicities observed with obinutuzumab are Hepatitis B virus (HBV) reactivation and progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy (PML). HBV reactivation can occur with all anti-CD20 antibodies and can result in hepatic failure, fulminant hepatitis, and death. PML occurs as a result of JC virus infection and can be fatal as well. Other common but less serious adverse reactions include infusion reactions (pre-treat with glucocorticoids, acetaminophen, and anti-histamine to prevent this), neutropenia, thrombocytopenia, and Tumor Lysis Syndrome (TLS) (pre-treat patients, especially with a high lymphocyte count and/or a high tumor burden, with anti-hyperuricemics and hydration). It is also recommended to NOT administer live virus vaccinations prior to or during obinutuzumab treatment.
drug.metabolism: Obinutuzumab is not metabolized by the liver.
drug.absorption: Obinutuzumab is administered intravenously, so its absorption is 100%.
drug.half-life: The half life of obinutuzumab is 28.4 days.
drug.protein-binding: Obinutuzumab does not bind to plasma proteins.
drug.route-of-elimination: The route of elimination of obinutuzumab was not indicated (FDA label).
drug.volume-of-distribution: Obinutuzumab has a volume of distribution of about 3.8 L.
